e different test paths, like using `JSON.std.with(JSON.Feature.USE_FIELDS)` for getDeclaredField.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring test coverage issues**\\n\\nI’m considering that there might not be a getDeclaredField on records because the current record class could be in another test file that isn’t included in the active test file mapping. This shouldn't impact coverage much, but perhaps the workflow only runs a single test file. It’s also possible that our test is using the same JSON.std singleton, which could lead to a cached reader that results in no line execution in the ValueReaderLocator test. The report might only reflect lines covered by the specific active class test file instead of the entire suite.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Thinking about data records**\\n\\nI’m considering whether to use an existing type in the metadata to avoid cache issues. Maybe I could define a new record in the same file, though it has unrelated modifications. I think I can still be careful with adding entries only to our hunks. Using `RecordsHelpersDynamicAccessTest.SampleRecord` sounds easier since it has the metadata, but I'm concerned about cache. If the report runs only active tests, there shouldn't be issues. Alternatively, a fresh JSON builder could help bypass caching altogether. It’s interesting to explore these options!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing test cache issues**\\n\\nI’m looking at our current test using `JSON.std`, which involves global cache. If other tests have already interacted with `SampleRecord`, the line I’m working on might not execute. Since the user mentioned previous attempts covered none, this could explain the getDeclaredField issue, but not the enum path, which uses a fresh JSON builder. However, one call site remains a mystery. I wonder whether the line coverage fails because `enumField(enumConstantName)` relies on `getField`, and in `POJODefinition.Prop`, perhaps there's no field for originalName. It’s a tricky situation!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering record modifications**\\n\\nI need to build a reader for the record while ensuring that BeanPropertyIntrospector and RecordsHelpers correctly access declared fields and constructors. Since the metadata for the record type is essential, I can add those type entries alongside the existing Direction enum field entries. However, I must be cautious about unrelated modifications and stage only my changes. Using `git add -p` for interactivity could work, but given the heavy modifications already made, selective staging is crucial. Scripting might help streamline this process.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Managing file modifications carefully**\\n\\nWith my existing file modifications being extensive and mostly unrelated, I need to check the differences and aim to stage just my specific changes. If I add my entry next to the existing Direction entry, the diff hunk might be smaller. I could try using `git add -p file <<<'y\\\\nq\\\\n'` to stage just one hunk, but if my changes are jumbled with others in a large diff, it could be complicated. An option could be creating a new metadata file under `src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/`, but I wonder if it needs a specific name to be recognized.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring metadata reuse**\\n\\nI could potentially avoid creating a new metadata file by reusing the existing `RecordsHelpersDynamicAccessTest.SampleRecord` type directly in the `findReader` call. Since the metadata is already in place, that seems pretty appealing. For the enum callsite, the Direction already has its metadata, so no edits would be necessary. The previous test might have failed due to using JSON.std cache and other complexities, but using a direct `findReader` call can leverage the same types, which should yield results. Let's check the existing metadata entries for SampleRecord to confirm.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering file changes**\\n\\nI’m thinking it's best to avoid making unrelated changes to files. Reusing what’s existing seems like a smart approach. For the enum, I can directly find the reader using the existing Direction within the same file, and a fresh locator should successfully hit it. It's possible that the previous JSON builder or extension did this as well, but I don't have any evidence of that. Direct methods seem to be more deterministic overall.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Checking enum deserialization tests**\\n\\nI’m thinking about recording a test to use a helper method called `valueReaderLocator(null).findReader(SampleRecord.class)`, and I should also look into actual deserialization. I might want to add a specific test for direct enum reader construction. The user is interested in coverage, so I can likely simplify things. I also need to inspect the JSONReader constructor signature, as it may require builders. Let’s dive into the JSONReader class!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_PohUg4O4EH4jYvDBVU2A43wL|fc_0ea263f7477fc9fd0169f02f4f54a0819499c339669ae46ac0", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge1/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/com.fasterxml.jackson.jr/jackson-jr-objects/2.21.0/main/extracted/com/fasterxml/jackson/jr/ob/impl/JSONReader.java", "offset": 1, "limit": 120}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.4", "usage": {"input": 14729, "output": 3267, "cacheRead": 44544, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 62540, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777348384609, "responseId": "resp_0ea263f7477fc9fd0169f02f212cec8194beea5caae20a373b"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_PohUg4O4EH4jYvDBVU2A43wL|fc_0ea263f7477fc9fd0169f02f4f54a0819499c339669ae46ac0", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "package com.fasterxml.jackson.jr.ob.impl;\n\nimport java.io.*;\nimport java.util.*;\n\nimport com.fasterxml.jackson.core.*;\nimport com.fasterxml.jackson.jr.ob.JSON;\nimport com.fasterxml.jackson.jr.ob.JSONObjectException;\nimport com.fasterxml.jackson.jr.ob.api.CollectionBuilder;\nimport com.fasterxml.jackson.jr.ob.api.MapBuilder;\nimport com.fasterxml.jackson.jr.ob.api.ValueReader;\n\n/**\n * Root-level helper object that handles initial delegation to actual\n * readers (which are {@link ValueReader}s), but does not handle\n * any of reading itself (despite name).\n *<p>\n * Life-cycle is such that initial instance (called blueprint)\n * is constructed first (including possible configuration\n * using mutant factory methods). This blueprint object\n * acts as a factory, and is never used for direct reading;\n * instead, per-call instance is created by calling\n * {@link #perOperationInstance}.\n */\npublic class JSONReader\n{\n    /*\n    /**********************************************************************\n    /* Blueprint config\n    /**********************************************************************\n     */\n\n    /**\n     * Handler that takes care of constructing {@link java.util.Map}s as needed\n     */\n    protected final MapBuilder _mapBuilder;\n\n    /**\n     * Handler that takes care of constructing {@link java.util.Map}s as needed\n     */\n    protected final CollectionBuilder _collectionBuilder;\n\n    /*\n    /**********************************************************************\n    /* Instance config, state\n    /**********************************************************************\n     */\n\n    protected final int _features;\n\n    /**\n     * Configured {@link TreeCodec} that is needed if values of type {@link TreeNode}\n     * are to be read.\n     */\n    protected final TreeCodec _treeCodec;\n\n    /**\n     * Object that is used to find value readers dynamically.\n     */\n    protected final ValueReaderLocator _readerLocator;\n\n    /**\n     * Parser used by